Undid last revision. Yes flute link should have been Western Concert Flute. But the rest is messed up (including broken half link). The designations are per the manuscript in Debussy's hand. Translation necessary too, like English horn for Cor Anglais, but the latter is common name too so need both there too.

Entire page completely rewritten. Basically I expanded it. Included lots of references. Wikilinks everywhere. Reformatted. Corrected everything from the previous page version. Now history, names, context, analyses, quotes, enjoy.
/* Transcription */ Removed superfluous text. Rewrote Benno Sachs sentence and added info.
/* Transcriptions */ Removed superflouous text and removed redlink.

/* Background */ Another slight syntax correction to the quoted translation of the same Mallarmé letter to Debussy. (The first source is what's quoted here, but that has a couple problems which I've now fixed; the second source is a different better translation but still with one word problem.)
/* Structure */ Added url and translator to ref.
/* Structure */ Added that the work is in cyclic form. Added a ref for the entire description.
/* Performance history */ Added publication info. Changed section name.

/* Instrumentation */ Corrected instrumentation. (I can tell this article was written by the same editor who wrote the Debussy Nocturnes article: it has the same errors and sloppy wording and misinformation and odd unsupported conclusions, and the exact same (erroneous) instrumentation too.) Corrections per the score on imslp. (I'll be fixing the entire Nocturnes article too by tonight...)
Added pronunciation. (Please fix this as English IPA or whatever. I just got tired of people saying "COR-tot", so I thought I should put some kind of pronunciation key.)
Common European (French) spelling of Alfred Cortot's surname, found in many references. English-speaking references, most particularly the U.S., omitted the circumflex.

Added spelling of his surname with the circumflex (common in Europe and French references). I don't have a source that states how he spelled it himself when a child or what was on his birth record, so I haven't clarified that.

/* Performance history */ Corrected premiere date (it was not on Armistice Day). Also corrected spelling of Cortôt's name (with the circumflex), and adjusted wikilink because WP actually spells it wrong and there is no #redirect (I'll fix that in a mo...)

/* Structure */ Rewrote because 1. It's in 3 movements not 2 (the 2nd to 3rd is without pause which is not unusual), and 2. to correctly explain what a concerto form truly is, compared to fantasia form (it's not just the number of movements, it's what's in them).
Just deleted the whole sentence anyway, because it's not Debussy's only composition for piano and orchestra (the harp solo of Sacred and Profane Dances he specified can be played on piano instead).

Removed redundancies in lead (already occur in main text). Deleted "even though it has three movements, it was not composed as a Piano Concerto" because that makes no sense (and also blatantly completely contradicts the statement in the section on Structure).
/* Performance history */ restored and rewrote a couple phrases. sounds better now.
/* Performance history */ Rearranged this paragraph for clarification, to eliminate apparent contradiction with Debussy both revising and discarding the work.

/* Robert Schumann's confinement and death */ Actually Robert was not in a mental or insane asylum (or lunatic asylum as they were called up to Schumann's time), he was in a sanatorium, quite a different type of institution, which explains better why he was admitted (not committed) at his own request. The institution was actually called "Richarz's Sanatorium" (''Richarz'sche Heilanstalt'').

/* Family life */ Clara was destroying letters Brahms wrote to her; Brahms asked her to destroy them. (Brahms didn't send her back her own letters to him for her to destroy, that wouldn't make sense: Brahms would have destroyed them himself.)
/* Concert tours */ Less verbiage and clearer. Also added comma back in as sentence meaning was incomprehensible.

Fixed Litzmann refs: 1913 not 2013, and all <ref> that were changed to {{sfn}} are vol. 2 Litzmann (vol. number was omitted in change).

For consistency and good form of citations, end all notes, references, sources, further reading, and external links with a period. {{cite}} and {{sfn}} templates add a period automatically; for the {{efn}} template or site templates such as {{IMSLP}} {{IMDB}} {{YOUTUBE}} etc, or plain <ref> with no template, need to add a period manually.

Reverting to previous correct (French) IPA pronunciation. English IPA not applicable as this is a French name. And we don't need several different mispronunciations from all those different sources; we all know English speakers mispronounce French names frequently and American and British dictionaries perpetuate those errors. One (correct) IPA is all we should have. Note: first name pronounced "yohsef" not "yawsef" so it was correct as "ʒozɛf" not "ʒɔzɛf"; same with middle name.

English IPA not applicable as this is a French name. And we don't need several different mispronunciations from all those different sources; we all know English speakers mispronounce French names frequently and American dictionaries perpetuate those errors. One (correct) IPA is all we should have.
